This will help you determine if the ground is cold enough to cause your bedding plants to freeze. Purchase a soil thermometer from any retail store that specializes in gardening products. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/90/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/9/90/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/aid1640788-v4-728px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Insert the soil thermometer into the ground between 10 and 15 cm (4 and 6 inches) to determine its temperature. Refer to the instructions provided by the soil thermometer's manufacturer to make sure it has been inserted properly for an accurate reading. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b2/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/b/b2/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/aid1640788-v4-728px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"547","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Freezing temperatures are below 0 degrees Celsius (0 degrees Fahrenheit). You may also want to cover your bedding plants if the temperature is slightly above freezing levels in the event the temperature continues to drop overnight. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e5/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/e/e5/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/aid1640788-v4-728px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Place layers of horticultural fleece over your bedding plants. Horticultural fleece is insulating material that will keep your plants warm during frost conditions but still expose them to air, rain, and light. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/76/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/aid1640788-v4-728px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":351,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"556","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Alternative forms of bedding plant covers are plastic tarps, newspapers, cardboard, bed linens, or similar types of light materials. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9b/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/9/9b/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/aid1640788-v4-728px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use heavy objects such as stones or jars to weigh down the sides of the protective covering. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3f/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/3/3f/Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/aid1640788-v4-728px-Protect-Bedding-Plants-from-Frost-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":352,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"557","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
